{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain explicit discussions of the normative (authoritative or doctrinal) weight of prose (*gadya*) versus verse (*śloka*, typically in *anuṣṭubh* meter) in Viṣṇu Smṛti or Nārada Smṛti.** \n\nViṣṇu Smṛti (unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8) consists entirely of verse chapters (100 total, all marked \"layout: verse\"), with no prose passages.[^1] Nārada Smṛti (unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2) is a single prose chapter (layout: prose), structured as legal procedural rules (*mātṛkās*) with numbered aphorisms (e.g., Nar. M1.1).[^2] No passages in either text—or related searches across Smṛtis like Manu Smṛti—compare their own forms' authority, nor explain when prose \"advances\" (elaborates/expands) or \"summarizes\" (*saṃgraha*).\n\nTraditional Dharmaśāstra scholarship (outside this corpus) often views *śloka* as core smṛti (higher authority) and prose as explanatory expansions, but this is not attested here. Searches for phrases like \"prose sloka smriti,\" \"normative weight,\" or \"authority prose verse\" yielded irrelevant modern French texts or incidental mentions (e.g., Manusmṛti 4.100 on Vedic prose vs. meter, not Smṛti).[^3]\n\n[^1]: From `get_metadata` and `list_chapters` for unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8; samples (Ch. 1, 6) confirm verse.[https://falsafa.thothica.com/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/01/translation/]\n\n[^2]: From `read_chapter` (Ch. 1, translation); continuous prose on vyavahāra (law). [https://falsafa.thothica.com/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/]\n\n[^3]: E.g., Manusmṛti 4.100, 8.49 (unrelated to Smṛti forms). [https://falsafa.thothica.com/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-8b8ea4]",
